{"title_page": "Cameo murder", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{notability|date=April 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = \n|court              = Liverpool Assizes\n|image              = \n|imagesize          = \n|imagelink          = \n|imagealt           = \n|caption            = \n|full name          = \n|date decided       = {{start date|1950|02|08|df=}}\n|citations          = \n|ECLI               = \n|transcripts        = \n|judges             = Mr Justice Roland Oliver\n|number of judges   = \n|decision by        = \n|concurring         = \n|dissenting         = \n|concur/dissent     = \n|prior actions      = \n|appealed from      = \n|appealed to        = [[Court of Criminal Appeal]]\n|subsequent actions = \n|related actions    = \n|opinions           = \n|keywords           = <!-- {{hlist | }} -->\n|italic title       = \n}}\nOn the evening of 19 March 1949,  the ''Cameo'' cinema in [[Liverpool]], [[England]], was the scene of a brutal double murder which led to a miscarriage of justice and the longest trial in British history at the time.<ref>George Skelly, ''The Cameo Conspiracy: A Shocking True Story of Murder and Injustice'', Waterside Press, p.11</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Call for Cameo murders inquiry|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7966136.stm|date=26 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nThe cinema manager, Leonard Thomas, was counting the day's takings assisted by his deputy, Bernard Catterall, when a masked man entered their office armed with a pistol. After demanding they hand over a bag of cash, which it appears they were reluctant to do, the man shot both of them fatally. Empty handed, the murderer then made his escape from the building, through an exit and down a fire escape, as other members of the cinema staff came to the men's aid.\n\n==Investigation==\n[[Liverpool City Police]] launched a huge manhunt for the killer, which turned up few leads until some months later when they received a letter from a pair of convicted criminals, a [[prostitute]] and her [[pimp]]. Jacqueline Dickson and James Northam were prepared to assist the police with information on the murders in return for immunity from prosecution themselves. This resulted in the arrests of two Liverpool men, '''Charles Connolly''', 26 and '''George Kelly''', 27. Kelly had convictions for petty theft whilst Connolly had been in trouble for brawling. Despite their protestations that they had never met before and both being able to produce sound alibis for the evening of 19 March, the pair were charged with the murder of the two men in the cinema.\n\n==First trial==\nThey stood trial at Liverpool [[Assizes (England and Wales)|Assizes]] in the city's [[St. George's Hall, Liverpool|St Georges Hall]] on 12 January 1950 before Mr. Justice Roland Oliver. The prosecution's case was that Kelly had been the gunman and that Connolly had acted as lookout as well as having planned the robbery.\n\n===Northam's evidence===\nIn his evidence, Northam alleged that he and Dickson had been present in the Bee Hive public house in Mount Pleasant with the defendants when they were plotting the crime; had seen Kelly loading a pistol; and that Kelly had borrowed his (Northam's) overcoat for use as a disguise during the robbery. Dickson stated that Kelly had borrowed a dark scarf or apron to use as a mask; trying it on in front of the customers of the crowded pub before he and Connolly boarded a tram to take them to the Edge Hill area. No other witnesses to this action were ever found. Northam claimed he had originally planned to assist in the robbery but the sight of the gun had frightened him off.\n\n===Graham's evidence===\nMuch was made of the evidence of Robert Graham, a [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] criminal serving a sentence in [[Liverpool (HM Prison)|Walton Prison]] at the same time that Kelly and Connolly were on remand there, who claimed to have carried messages between the prisoners as they sat in adjacent cells, which would have been unnecessary as the cells, which had barred doors rather than solid ones,  were near enough that the men could converse freely. He also alleged that both Kelly and Connolly had separately confessed their part in the murders to him in the exercise yard, which both men denied. Graham was later rewarded for his evidence with a reduction in his sentence. \n                     \nKelly had spent almost the whole day and early evening of the murder drinking heavily and many witnesses came forward to confirm the fact that he was clearly half drunk as the day wore on. The cinema staff however, were quite certain the man who threatened them outside the manager's office before sprinting out of the building and away up a side street, so quickly they could not keep up with him, was not somebody who had been drinking. Forensic examination of the crime scene and the angle of the bullet wounds in the victims' bodies indicated that the person who fired the shots had held the gun in his left hand. The cinema fireman, who witnessed the gunman leaving through the fire exit, noted that he kept his left hand, presumably holding his gun, in his pocket. Kelly was right-handed.\n\nAfter what was then one of the longest murder trials in British legal history, the jury failed to reach a verdict and a retrial was ordered, this time with the defendants tried separately.\n\n===Where was Charles Connolly ===\nMuch was made of the question of where Charles Connolly had been at the time of the shooting <ref name=\":0\">{{cite website|title=Unsolved Murders - Bernard Catterall|url=http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=6707#browse|work=Unsolved Murders|date=16 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\":1\">{{cite website|title=Unsolved Murders - Leonard Thomas|url=http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=2221#browse|work=Unsolved Murders|date=16 April 2020}}</ref> as it was said that his role was that of lookout. However, he was not seen near the cinema and the sequence of events tended to preclude him having played any role as look out as he neither warned George Kelly of John Catterall's arrival at the managers office nor appeared to have been standing ready at the emergency exit which the gunman clearly had trouble opening. This led to the question of how the gunman entered the cinema, the conclusion being that he must have either gone through the auditorium of from the main entrance, or that there had been an accomplice who had opened the emergency exit from the inside in advance.\n\n===The mystery of the cut telephone wires ===\nThe telephone wires at the Cameo Cinema had been cut at the foot of the spiral staircase <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> and the police were called by a local resident although they arrived quickly. However, no explanation was put forward for who cut them and when. The issue of the cut wires is further complicated when considering the evidence of Northam, Dickson and Graham, none of whom detailed the issue in the planning. In particular, if the robbery had been planned in the Beehive Hotel earlier in the evening then it might have been reasonable to consider that the conversation would have addressed the need or intention to cut the phone wires and whether anyone had a tool that they could be cut with. Nor is the cutting of the telephone wires detailed in Northam's subsequent conversation in the following days with george Kelly when he allegedly explained what happened. The ommission of this fact that only the murderer would have known and which was either not reported in the newspapers or only reported in the most extensive coverage, being a significant part of the robbery that would have taken time, of which there were only a few minutes from start to finish, undermines the veracity of Northam, Dickson and Graham's subseqent accounts of George Kellys alleged confessions.\n\n===2 February 1949 Cameo Cinema break in ===\nLittle is made of the break in at the Cameo Cinema on 2 February 1949 <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> for which three youths were arrested and charged on 2 April 1949. During the break in they had gone into the manager's office, where Leonard Thomas and John Catterall were later shot and tried forcing cupboards. They took cigarettes, chocolate and 10s, worth in total about \u00a35, but would no doubt have familiarised themselves with the office layout and seen the safe. Whilst there is nothing connecting them with the murder, where was nothing connecting  Charles Connolly or George Kelly with the murder either other than false statements and circumstantial behaviour. The significance of the 2 February 1949 break in was that it suggests that the Cameo Cinema was a target with local youths and criminals for easy pickings and that there could have been any number of other people with an interest in the venue with regards to robbing it after word spread about the lay out and discussion was had about how they handled their money.   \n\n==Re-trial==\nKelly was tried first and, despite a spirited defence by [[Rose Heilbron]] [[King's Counsel|KC]], he was found guilty and sentenced to death. The just was [[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]]. Connolly was then offered the chance to plead guilty to conspiracy and being an accessory. Faced with the almost certainty that he would otherwise be convicted of murder and share the fate of his co-accused if he refused, he had little choice other than to accept the offer and plead accordingly. Contrary to popular belief, Connolly did not [[turn state's evidence|turn King's Evidence]] but simply pleaded guilty to the charges laid before him. His  plea however, destroyed Kelly's assertions of his own innocence and despite an appeal against his conviction, Kelly was executed at [[Liverpool (HM Prison)|Walton Prison]], [[Liverpool]] by [[Albert Pierrepoint]] and his assistant [[Harry Allen (executioner)|Harry Allen]] on 28 March 1950. He continued to assert his innocence, even on the scaffold. Connolly was released from prison in 1957 and died in 1997. Shortly before his death, he took part in an interview on [[BBC Radio Merseyside]], during which he reaffirmed both his and Kelly's innocence.\n\n===[[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]]===\n[[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]] was the judge at the second trial. After the convictions were handed down he commended Northam and Dickson and awarded them \u00a330 each for their selfless role in the case and recommended that Graham be similarly have a good word given although he could not reward him directly under his powers <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" />. [[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]] said 'but for their evidence, George Kelly and Charles Connolly, two dangerous criminals might never had been brought to justice. Whatever their previous faults might have been, they, by their actions in the case, and at the risk to their personal safety, had rendered a service to the community'. Dickson, who was already a convicted prostitute, went on two years later to be convicted for violently robbing her clients and was sentenced to a number of years imprisonment. Northam had a large number of convcitions.\n\n==Controversy==\nThe case caused considerable disquiet in legal circles for many years and there were a number of attempts to have it re-opened. The evidence put forward by the prosecution had emanated from witnesses who could hardly be described as being of sterling character. Dickson was a convicted prostitute and thief who, two years after the Cameo trial, was sentenced  with others to a lengthy prison term for the violent robberies of a number of her clients. Northam had been a criminal since the age of 14 and had spent much of the 1940s in and out of prison. Graham shared a similar background. All three stood to gain by their testimony. The detective who led the investigation, Detective Chief Inspector Herbert Balmer, had difficulty in corroborating much of the prosecution evidence during the trial and many prosecution witness statements bore the sign of police coaching. Employer's timesheets, which detailed Connolly's movements on the day of the murder, had been amateurishly tampered with. Witness statements that favoured the accused men were held back by the police, a fact later discovered by a local businessman, Luigi Santangeli, who set out to investigate the crime on behalf of Connolly in the 1990s and was given access to the case files by [[Merseyside Police]].\n\n===Donald Johnson===\nMost importantly, scant attention was paid to the fact that another Liverpool criminal, Donald Johnson, had demonstrated an intimate knowledge of the crime after being arrested for a street robbery in [[Birkenhead]] and had been charged with complicity in the murders prior to the arrests of Kelly and Connolly. Johnson had been transferred to Walton Prison from Birkenhead, where he allegedly admitted to another prisoner that he had been involved in the cinema shootings. This other prisoner was Robert Graham, the same witness who would later tell the court that Connolly and Kelly had confessed to being the murderers. During questioning, Johnson admitted being in the vicinity of the cinema at the time of the murders and had been stopped by a police constable, suspicious of his loitering, who had demanded to see his identity card and then taken his name. Johnson, during police interrogation, referred to the murder weapon as being an automatic, a fact which the police had not made known to the public. He further stated that one of the dead men had been shot whilst on his hands and knees, another fact which had been held back by the police. Johnson also told police that he knew the identity of the gunman, but had taken a religious oath not to reveal his name.\n\nBecause Johnson's  entire statement was ruled inadmissible, after the presiding judge decided that the police had obtained it by threats and inducement, an attempt to try him as an accessory failed and he was freed. Liverpool City Police were then left in the position of having lost their most likely suspect - who could not be even questioned about the case again. Given the magnitude of the crime, reputations and careers would no doubt have been in jeopardy and the investigation team were in desperate need of fresh suspects. Donald Johnson later claimed that he had lied about what he knew of the shooting in the hope that he could get the police to dismiss his Birkenhead offence. Confessing to even peripheral involvement in a brutal double murder however, simply to have a mere mugging charge dismissed, would seem an unlikely course of action for an experienced criminal like Johnson to take and he clearly had a detailed knowledge of what had occurred in the cinema office. There has been speculation in the years since that a close relative of Johnson's may have been the gunman and that was the reason he refused to name him to the police. Johnson died in 1988.                         \nEventually the case reached the [[Court of Criminal Appeal]] in February 2001 and in June 2003 Kelly's and Connolly's convictions were judged to be unsafe and were duly quashed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siddle|first1=John|title=ECHO Murder Files: The double murders which rocked post-war Liverpool|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/echo-murder-files-double-murders-9269795|work=liverpoolecho|date=16 May 2015}}</ref> Kelly's remains were taken from their burial place in Walton prison by his family and he was given a dignified funeral after a service in [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shennan|first1=Paddy|title=Cameo Cinema murders - Wallasey author working on screenplay for film wants Hollywood star Stephen Graham in lead role|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/cameo-cinema-murders-wallasey-author-9797586|work=liverpoolecho|date=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Related case==\nTwo years after the execution, Chief Superintendent Balmer was investigating the murder of Beatrice Rimmer in Cranborne Road, just a few hundred yards from the Cameo cinema. He was again claiming that two young men, this time from Manchester, Alfred Burns and Edward Devlin, were responsible for the crime. Their convictions were clearly shown to be unsafe in a book, Murderers Or Martyrs (Waterside Press 2013), again by George Skelly, with a damning foreword by former UK Attorney General Lord Goldsmith QC. Indeed, the author demonstrated in detail how Balmer may have framed the two men in an identical scenario to that used by him to frame Kelly and Connolly two years earlier. The possibility that Balmer did frame the two men is more tenuous than in the Cameo case and probably explains why Skelly's submission to the Criminal Cases Review Commission, involving new argument and eleven bundles of previously undisclosed evidence, was rejected.\n<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shennan|first1=Paddy|title=Liverpool murders investigated by author George Skelly|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/liverpool-murders-investigated-author-george-3323765|work=liverpoolecho|date=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Cameo Murders]]'' (book)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20060623073925/http://www.innocent.org.uk/cases/georgekelly/index.html\n*https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/stevenhortonuk/cameomurders.html&date=2009-10-25+22:22:53\n*http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=2221#browse\n*http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=6707#browse\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cameo Murder}}\n[[Category:1949 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1949 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1949 in England]]\n[[Category:1940s in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:History of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Murder in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{notability|date=April 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = \n|court              = Liverpool Assizes\n|image              = \n|imagesize          = \n|imagelink          = \n|imagealt           = \n|caption            = \n|full name          = \n|date decided       = {{start date|1950|02|08|df=}}\n|citations          = \n|ECLI               = \n|transcripts        = \n|judges             = Mr Justice Roland Oliver\n|number of judges   = \n|decision by        = \n|concurring         = \n|dissenting         = \n|concur/dissent     = \n|prior actions      = \n|appealed from      = \n|appealed to        = [[Court of Criminal Appeal]]\n|subsequent actions = \n|related actions    = \n|opinions           = \n|keywords           = <!-- {{hlist | }} -->\n|italic title       = \n}}\nOn the evening of 19 March 1949,  the ''Cameo'' cinema in [[Liverpool]], [[England]], was the scene of a brutal double murder which led to a miscarriage of justice and the longest trial in British history at the time.<ref>George Skelly, ''The Cameo Conspiracy: A Shocking True Story of Murder and Injustice'', Waterside Press, p.11</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Call for Cameo murders inquiry|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7966136.stm|date=26 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nThe cinema manager, Leonard Thomas, was counting the day's takings assisted by his deputy, Bernard Catterall, when a masked man entered their office armed with a pistol. After demanding they hand over a bag of cash, which it appears they were reluctant to do, the man shot both of them fatally. Empty handed, the murderer then made his escape from the building, through an exit and down a fire escape, as other members of the cinema staff came to the men's aid.\n\n==Investigation==\n[[Liverpool City Police]] launched a huge manhunt for the killer, which turned up few leads until some months later when they received a letter from a pair of convicted criminals, a [[prostitute]] and her [[pimp]]. Jacqueline Dickson and James Northam were prepared to assist the police with information on the murders in return for immunity from prosecution themselves. This resulted in the arrests of two Liverpool men, '''Charles Connolly''', 26 and '''George Kelly''', 27. Kelly had convictions for petty theft whilst Connolly had been in trouble for brawling. Despite their protestations that they had never met before and both being able to produce sound alibis for the evening of 19 March, the pair were charged with the murder of the two men in the cinema.\n\n==First trial==\nThey stood trial at Liverpool [[Assizes (England and Wales)|Assizes]] in the city's [[St. George's Hall, Liverpool|St Georges Hall]] on 12 January 1950 before Mr. Justice Roland Oliver. The prosecution's case was that Kelly had been the gunman and that Connolly had acted as lookout as well as having planned the robbery.\n\n===Northam's evidence===\nIn his evidence, Northam alleged that he and Dickson had been present in the Bee Hive public house in Mount Pleasant with the defendants when they were plotting the crime; had seen Kelly loading a pistol; and that Kelly had borrowed his (Northam's) overcoat for use as a disguise during the robbery. Dickson stated that Kelly had borrowed a dark scarf or apron to use as a mask; trying it on in front of the customers of the crowded pub before he and Connolly boarded a tram to take them to the Edge Hill area. No other witnesses to this action were ever found. Northam claimed he had originally planned to assist in the robbery but the sight of the gun had frightened him off.\n\n===Graham's evidence===\nMuch was made of the evidence of Robert Graham, a [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] criminal serving a sentence in [[Liverpool (HM Prison)|Walton Prison]] at the same time that Kelly and Connolly were on remand there, who claimed to have carried messages between the prisoners as they sat in adjacent cells, which would have been unnecessary as the cells, which had barred doors rather than solid ones,  were near enough that the men could converse freely. He also alleged that both Kelly and Connolly had separately confessed their part in the murders to him in the exercise yard, which both men denied. Graham was later rewarded for his evidence with a reduction in his sentence. \n                     \nKelly had spent almost the whole day and early evening of the murder drinking heavily and many witnesses came forward to confirm the fact that he was clearly half drunk as the day wore on. The cinema staff however, were quite certain the man who threatened them outside the manager's office before sprinting out of the building and away up a side street, so quickly they could not keep up with him, was not somebody who had been drinking. Forensic examination of the crime scene and the angle of the bullet wounds in the victims' bodies indicated that the person who fired the shots had held the gun in his left hand. The cinema fireman, who witnessed the gunman leaving through the fire exit, noted that he kept his left hand, presumably holding his gun, in his pocket. Kelly was right-handed.\n\nAfter what was then one of the longest murder trials in British legal history, the jury failed to reach a verdict and a retrial was ordered, this time with the defendants tried separately.\n\n===Where was Charles Connolly ===\nMuch was made of the question of where Charles Connolly had been at the time of the shooting <ref name=\":0\">{{cite website|title=Unsolved Murders - Bernard Catterall|url=http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=6707#browse|work=Unsolved Murders|date=16 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\":1\">{{cite website|title=Unsolved Murders - Leonard Thomas|url=http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=2221#browse|work=Unsolved Murders|date=16 April 2020}}</ref> as it was said that his role was that of lookout. However, he was not seen near the cinema and the sequence of events tended to preclude him having played any role as look out as he neither warned George Kelly of John Catterall's arrival at the managers office nor appeared to have been standing ready at the emergency exit which the gunman clearly had trouble opening. This led to the question of how the gunman entered the cinema, the conclusion being that he must have either gone through the auditorium of from the main entrance, or that there had been an accomplice who had opened the emergency exit from the inside in advance.\n\n===The mystery of the cut telephone wires ===\nThe telephone wires at the Cameo Cinema had been cut at the foot of the spiral staircase <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> and the police were called by a local resident although they arrived quickly. However, no explanation was put forward for who cut them and when. The issue of the cut wires is further complicated when considering the evidence of Northam, Dickson and Graham, none of whom detailed the issue in the planning. In particular, if the robbery had been planned in the Beehive Hotel earlier in the evening then it might have been reasonable to consider that the conversation would have addressed the need or intention to cut the phone wires and whether anyone had a tool that they could be cut with. Nor is the cutting of the telephone wires detailed in Northam's subsequent conversation in the following days with george Kelly when he allegedly explained what happened. The ommission of this fact that only the murderer would have known and which was either not reported in the newspapers or only reported in the most extensive coverage, being a significant part of the robbery that would have taken time, of which there were only a few minutes from start to finish, undermines the veracity of Northam, Dickson and Graham's subseqent accounts of George Kellys alleged confessions.\n\n===2 February 1949 Cameo Cinema break in ===\nLittle is made of the break in at the Cameo Cinema on 2 February 1949 <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> for which three youths were arrested and charged on 2 April 1949. During the break in they had gone into the manager's office, where Leonard Thomas and John Catterall were later shot and tried forcing cupboards. They took cigarettes, chocolate and 10s, worth in total about \u00a35, but would no doubt have familiarised themselves with the office layout and seen the safe. Whilst there is nothign connecting them with the murder, where was nothing connecting  Charles Connolly or George Kelly with the murder either other than false statements and circumstantial behaviour. The significance of the 2 February 1949 break in was that it suggests that the Cameo Cinema was a target with local youths and criminals for easy pickings and that there could have been any number of other people with an interest in the venue with regards to robbing it after word spread about the lay out and discussion was had about how they handled their money.   \n\n==Re-trial==\nKelly was tried first and, despite a spirited defence by [[Rose Heilbron]] [[King's Counsel|KC]], he was found guilty and sentenced to death. The just was [[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]]. Connolly was then offered the chance to plead guilty to conspiracy and being an accessory. Faced with the almost certainty that he would otherwise be convicted of murder and share the fate of his co-accused if he refused, he had little choice other than to accept the offer and plead accordingly. Contrary to popular belief, Connolly did not [[turn state's evidence|turn King's Evidence]] but simply pleaded guilty to the charges laid before him. His  plea however, destroyed Kelly's assertions of his own innocence and despite an appeal against his conviction, Kelly was executed at [[Liverpool (HM Prison)|Walton Prison]], [[Liverpool]] by [[Albert Pierrepoint]] and his assistant [[Harry Allen (executioner)|Harry Allen]] on 28 March 1950. He continued to assert his innocence, even on the scaffold. Connolly was released from prison in 1957 and died in 1997. Shortly before his death, he took part in an interview on [[BBC Radio Merseyside]], during which he reaffirmed both his and Kelly's innocence.\n\n===[[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]]===\n[[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]] was the judge at the second trial. After the convictions were handed down he commended Northam and Dickson and awarded them \u00a330 each for their selfless role in the case and recommended that Graham be similarly have a good word given although he could not reward him directly under his powers <ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" />. [[James Cassels (politician)|Justice Cassels]] said 'but for their evidence, George Kelly and Charles Connolly, two dangerous criminals might never had been brought to justice. Whatever their previous faults might have been, they, by their actions in the case, and at the risk to their personal safety, had rendered a service to the community'. Dickson, who was already a convicted prostitute, went on two years later to be convicted for violently robbing her clients and was sentenced to a number of years imprisonment. Northam had a large number of convcitions.\n\n==Controversy==\nThe case caused considerable disquiet in legal circles for many years and there were a number of attempts to have it re-opened. The evidence put forward by the prosecution had emanated from witnesses who could hardly be described as being of sterling character. Dickson was a convicted prostitute and thief who, two years after the Cameo trial, was sentenced  with others to a lengthy prison term for the violent robberies of a number of her clients. Northam had been a criminal since the age of 14 and had spent much of the 1940s in and out of prison. Graham shared a similar background. All three stood to gain by their testimony. The detective who led the investigation, Detective Chief Inspector Herbert Balmer, had difficulty in corroborating much of the prosecution evidence during the trial and many prosecution witness statements bore the sign of police coaching. Employer's timesheets, which detailed Connolly's movements on the day of the murder, had been amateurishly tampered with. Witness statements that favoured the accused men were held back by the police, a fact later discovered by a local businessman, Luigi Santangeli, who set out to investigate the crime on behalf of Connolly in the 1990s and was given access to the case files by [[Merseyside Police]].\n\n===Donald Johnson===\nMost importantly, scant attention was paid to the fact that another Liverpool criminal, Donald Johnson, had demonstrated an intimate knowledge of the crime after being arrested for a street robbery in [[Birkenhead]] and had been charged with complicity in the murders prior to the arrests of Kelly and Connolly. Johnson had been transferred to Walton Prison from Birkenhead, where he allegedly admitted to another prisoner that he had been involved in the cinema shootings. This other prisoner was Robert Graham, the same witness who would later tell the court that Connolly and Kelly had confessed to being the murderers. During questioning, Johnson admitted being in the vicinity of the cinema at the time of the murders and had been stopped by a police constable, suspicious of his loitering, who had demanded to see his identity card and then taken his name. Johnson, during police interrogation, referred to the murder weapon as being an automatic, a fact which the police had not made known to the public. He further stated that one of the dead men had been shot whilst on his hands and knees, another fact which had been held back by the police. Johnson also told police that he knew the identity of the gunman, but had taken a religious oath not to reveal his name.\n\nBecause Johnson's  entire statement was ruled inadmissible, after the presiding judge decided that the police had obtained it by threats and inducement, an attempt to try him as an accessory failed and he was freed. Liverpool City Police were then left in the position of having lost their most likely suspect - who could not be even questioned about the case again. Given the magnitude of the crime, reputations and careers would no doubt have been in jeopardy and the investigation team were in desperate need of fresh suspects. Donald Johnson later claimed that he had lied about what he knew of the shooting in the hope that he could get the police to dismiss his Birkenhead offence. Confessing to even peripheral involvement in a brutal double murder however, simply to have a mere mugging charge dismissed, would seem an unlikely course of action for an experienced criminal like Johnson to take and he clearly had a detailed knowledge of what had occurred in the cinema office. There has been speculation in the years since that a close relative of Johnson's may have been the gunman and that was the reason he refused to name him to the police. Johnson died in 1988.                         \nEventually the case reached the [[Court of Criminal Appeal]] in February 2001 and in June 2003 Kelly's and Connolly's convictions were judged to be unsafe and were duly quashed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siddle|first1=John|title=ECHO Murder Files: The double murders which rocked post-war Liverpool|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/echo-murder-files-double-murders-9269795|work=liverpoolecho|date=16 May 2015}}</ref> Kelly's remains were taken from their burial place in Walton prison by his family and he was given a dignified funeral after a service in [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shennan|first1=Paddy|title=Cameo Cinema murders - Wallasey author working on screenplay for film wants Hollywood star Stephen Graham in lead role|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/cameo-cinema-murders-wallasey-author-9797586|work=liverpoolecho|date=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Related case==\nTwo years after the execution, Chief Superintendent Balmer was investigating the murder of Beatrice Rimmer in Cranborne Road, just a few hundred yards from the Cameo cinema. He was again claiming that two young men, this time from Manchester, Alfred Burns and Edward Devlin, were responsible for the crime. Their convictions were clearly shown to be unsafe in a book, Murderers Or Martyrs (Waterside Press 2013), again by George Skelly, with a damning foreword by former UK Attorney General Lord Goldsmith QC. Indeed, the author demonstrated in detail how Balmer may have framed the two men in an identical scenario to that used by him to frame Kelly and Connolly two years earlier. The possibility that Balmer did frame the two men is more tenuous than in the Cameo case and probably explains why Skelly's submission to the Criminal Cases Review Commission, involving new argument and eleven bundles of previously undisclosed evidence, was rejected.\n<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shennan|first1=Paddy|title=Liverpool murders investigated by author George Skelly|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/liverpool-murders-investigated-author-george-3323765|work=liverpoolecho|date=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Cameo Murders]]'' (book)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20060623073925/http://www.innocent.org.uk/cases/georgekelly/index.html\n*https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/stevenhortonuk/cameomurders.html&date=2009-10-25+22:22:53\n*http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=2221#browse\n*http://www.unsolved-murders.co.uk/murder-content.php?key=6707#browse\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cameo Murder}}\n[[Category:1949 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1949 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1949 in England]]\n[[Category:1940s in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:History of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Murder in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Helpmechoose837", "label": "safe", "comment": "one typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cameo_murder"}
{"title_page": "Harry Hampton", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Harry Hampton\n|image= Harry Hampton VC.jpg\n|caption= \n|birth_date= 14 December 1870\n|birth_place= [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], [[Surrey]], England\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|df=yes|1922|11|02|1870|12|14}}\n|death_place= [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]], England\n|placeofburial= Richmond Cemetery\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= \n|rank= [[Colour Sergeant]]\n|commands= \n|unit= [[The King's (Liverpool) Regiment]]\n|battles= [[Second Boer War]]\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]\n|laterwork=\n|relations=\n}}\n'''Harry Hampton''' [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (14 December 1870 \u2013 2 November 1922) was an English recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces.\n\n== Details ==\nHampton was born in Crown Terrace, [[Richmond, London|Richmond (then in Surrey and now in London)]] on 14 December 1870.<ref name=\"Richmond\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/victoria_cross_holders_buried_in_the_borough/harry_hampton.htm | title=Harry Hampton | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Victoria Cross holders buried in the borough | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=4 November 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104061756/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/victoria_cross_holders_buried_in_the_borough/harry_hampton.htm | archivedate=4 November 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHampton was 29 years old, and a [[sergeant]] in the 2nd Battalion, [[The King's (Liverpool) Regiment]], [[British Army]] during the [[Second Boer War]] when the following deed took place on 21 August 1900 at [[Van Wyk's Vlei]], South Africa, for which he was awarded the VC:\n{{quote|On the 21st August, 1900, at Van Wyk's Vlei, Sergeant Hampton, who was in command of a small party of Mounted Infantry, held an important position for some time against heavy odds, and when compelled to retire saw all his men into safety, and then, although he had himself been wounded in the head, supported Lance-Corporal Walsh, who was unable to walk, until the latter was again hit and apparently killed, Sergeant Hampton himself being again wounded a short time after.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27366|page=6779|date=18 October 1901}}</ref>}}\n\nHe received the decoration from [[King Edward VII]], in person, during an investiture at [[St James's Palace]] on 17 December 1901.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court circular |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=18 December 1901 |page_number=6 |issue=36641}}</ref>\n\n==Further information==\nHampton later achieved the rank of [[colour sergeant]]. He retired from the Army after the [[First World War]] and returned to the Richmond area, taking employment in the City of London as a [[commissionaire]] with a firm of [[solicitors]]. In 1919 whilst dismounting from a bus in Richmond his leg, injured during the Boer War, gave way. He continued to live at the family home of 151 Halliburton Road, [[St Margarets, London|St Margarets]], [[Twickenham]] until his fatal accident in November 1922.\n\nHampton died in Twickenham on 2 November 1922.<ref name=\"Richmond\"/> Although reported as having taken his own life by jumping in front of a train at [[Richmond station (London)|Richmond]] rail station, he did in fact succumb to multiple injuries sustained from falling against a [[Shepperton]] train passing through [[St Margarets (London) railway station|St Margarets railway station]] in Twickenham. In the subsequent inquest there was no suggestion that he might have taken his own life, the opinion of the coroner being that a leg injured when he had fallen from a bus approximately two years before his death had given way as the Shepperton train passed through St Margarets station.\n\nHis funeral was held in St Margarets, after which his coffin was carried on a gun carriage with a military escort. He was conveyed from St Margarets, across Richmond Bridge, and on arriving outside Richmond Town Hall, the Mayor, Councillors, and a crowd of several thousand had assembled to pay their respects, many of which then followed the gun carriage to [[Richmond Cemetery]].\n\nHe is buried in [[Richmond Cemetery]],<ref name=\"Richmond\"/> but for over 50 years his grave remained unmarked. In 1986 the location of the grave was re-discovered by Ron Buddle, a [[Metropolitan Police|Metropolitan police officer]] and Victoria Cross historian who, with financial assistance from the King's Regiment Association, erected the present headstone. However, the date of death shown on the headstone of 4 February 1920 was incorrect, the error being corrected when the grave was restored in 2008 as part of the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]' \"Adopt a Grave\" scheme.{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}}\n\n==The medal==\nHis Victoria Cross is displayed at the [[Museum of the King's Regiment]] in Liverpool, England.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Buzzell, Nora (1997). ''[[The Register of the Victoria Cross]]'', ''[[This England (magazine)|This England]]''. Third ed., 352 pp. {{ISBN|0-906324-27-0}} \n*[[David Charles Harvey|Harvey, David]] (1999). ''[[Monuments to Courage|Monuments to Courage: Victoria Cross Headstones and Memorials]]'' Vol.2, 1917\u20131982. Kevin & Kay Patience. OCLC 59437300 \n* Uys, Ian (2000). ''[[Victoria Crosses of the Anglo-Boer War]]''\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041204085907/http://www.homeusers.prestel.co.uk/stewart/surrey.htm Location of grave and VC medal] ''(Surrey)''\n*[http://www.angloboerwar.com/medals-and-awards/12-victoria-cross/191-hampton-harry Angloboerwar.com]\n\n{{Duke of Lancaster's Regiment}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hampton, Harry}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:British Army recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:British recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:Burials at Richmond Cemetery]]\n[[Category:King's Regiment (Liverpool) soldiers]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, London]]\n[[Category:Railway accident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Second Boer War recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Harry Hampton\n|image= Harry Hampton VC.jpg\n|caption= \n|birth_date= 14 December 1870\n|birth_place= [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], [[Surrey]], England\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|df=yes|1922|11|02|1870|12|14}}\n|death_place= [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]], England\n|placeofburial= Richmond Cemetery\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= \n|rank= [[Colour Sergeant]]\n|commands= \n|unit= [[The King's (Liverpool) Regiment]]\n|battles= [[Second Boer War]]\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]\n|laterwork=\n|relations=\n}}\n'''Harry Hampton''' [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (14 December 1870 \u2013 2 November 1922) was an English recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces.\n\n== Details ==\nHampton was born in Crown Terrace, [[Richmond, London|Richmond (then in Surrey and now in London)]] on 14 December 1870.<ref name=\"Richmond\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/victoria_cross_holders_buried_in_the_borough/harry_hampton.htm | title=Harry Hampton | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Victoria Cross holders buried in the borough | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=4 November 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104061756/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/victoria_cross_holders_buried_in_the_borough/harry_hampton.htm | archivedate=4 November 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHampton was 29 years old, and a [[sergeant]] in the 2nd Battalion, [[The King's (Liverpool) Regiment]], [[British Army]] during the [[Second Boer War]] when the following deed took place on 21 August 1900 at [[Van Wyk's Vlei]], South Africa, for which he was awarded the VC:\n{{quote|On the 21st August, 1900, at Van Wyk's Vlei, Sergeant Hampton, who was in command of a small party of Mounted Infantry, held an important position for some time against heavy odds, and when compelled to retire saw all his men into safety, and then, although he had himself been wounded in the head, supported Lance-Corporal Walsh, who was unable to walk, until the latter was again hit and apparently killed, Sergeant Hampton himself being again wounded a short time after.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27366|page=6779|date=18 October 1901}}</ref>}}\n\nHe received the decoration from [[King Edward VII]], in person, during an investiture at [[St James's Palace]] on 17 December 1901.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court circular |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=18 December 1901 |page_number=6 |issue=36641}}</ref>\n\n==Further information==\nHampton later achieved the rank of [[colour sergeant]]. He retired from the Army after the [[First World War]] and returned to the Richmond area, taking employment in the City of London as a [[commissionaire]] with a firm of [[solicitors]]. In 1919 whilst dismounting from a bus in Richmond his leg, injured during the Boer War, gave way. He continued to live at the family home of 151 Halliburton Road, [[St Margarets, London|St Margarets]], [[Twickenham]] until his fatal accident in November 1922.\n\nHampton died in Twickenham on 2 November 1922.<ref name=\"Richmond\"/> Although reported as having taken his own life by jumping in front of a train at [[Richmond station (London)|Richmond]] rail station, he did in fact succumb to multiple injuries sustained from falling against a [[Shepperton]] train passing through [[St Margarets (London) railway station|St Margarets railway station]] in Twickenham. In the subsequent inquest there was no suggestion that he might have taken his own life, the opinion of the coroner being that a leg injured when he had fallen from a bus approximately two years before his death had given way as the Shepperton train passed through St Margarets station.\n\nHis funeral was held in St Margarets, after which his coffin was carried on a gun carriage with a military escort. He was conveyed from St Margarets, across Richmond Bridge, and on arriving outside Richmond Town Hall, the Mayor, Councillors, and a crowd of several thousand had assembled to pay their respects, many of which then followed the gun carriage to [[Richmond Cemetery]].\n\nHe is buried in [[Richmond Cemetery]],<ref name=\"Richmond\"/> but for over 50 years his grave remained unmarked. In 1986 the location of the grave was re-discovered by Ron Buddle, a [[Metropolitan Police|Metropolitan police officer]] and Victoria Cross historian who, with financial assistance from the King's Regiment Association, erected the present headstone. However, the date of death shown on the headstone of 4 February 1920 was incorrect, the error being corrected when the grave was restored in 2008 as part of the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]' \"Adopt a Grave\" scheme.{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}}\n\n==The medal==\nHis Victoria Cross is displayed at the [[Museum of the King's Regiment]] in Liverpool, England.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[David Charles Harvey|Harvey, David]] (1999). ''[[Monuments to Courage|Monuments to Courage: Victoria Cross Headstones and Memorials]]'' Vol.2, 1917\u20131982. Kevin & Kay Patience. OCLC 59437300 \n*Buzzell. Nora (1997). ''[[The Register of the Victoria Cross]]'', ''[[This England (magazine)|This England]]''. Third ed., 352 pp. {{ISBN|0-906324-27-0}} \n* Uys, Ian (2000). ''[[Victoria Crosses of the Anglo-Boer War]]''\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041204085907/http://www.homeusers.prestel.co.uk/stewart/surrey.htm Location of grave and VC medal] ''(Surrey)''\n*[http://www.angloboerwar.com/medals-and-awards/12-victoria-cross/191-hampton-harry Angloboerwar.com]\n\n{{Duke of Lancaster's Regiment}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hampton, Harry}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:British Army recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:British recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:Burials at Richmond Cemetery]]\n[[Category:King's Regiment (Liverpool) soldiers]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, London]]\n[[Category:Railway accident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Second Boer War recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:Reordered", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Hampton"}
{"title_page": "Southard, New Jersey", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Southard, New Jersey\n|settlement_type          = [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA New Jersey Monmouth County#USA New Jersey#USA\n|pushpin_label_position   = left\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location of Southard in Monmouth County Inset: Location of county within the state of New Jersey\n|pushpin_map1             =\n|pushpin_label_position1  =\n|pushpin_map_caption1     =\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|New Jersey}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in New Jersey|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Howell Township, New Jersey|Howell]]\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=GNIS/>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 118\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|08|18|N|74|13|30|W|region:US-NJ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info               = 880764<ref name=GNIS>{{cite gnis|880764|Southard}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref                = imperial\n}}\n'''Southard''' is an [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|unincorporated community]] located within [[Howell Township, New Jersey|Howell Township]] in [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth County]], [[New Jersey]], United States centered around [[U.S. Route 9 in New Jersey|U.S. Route 9]].<ref>{{cite web  |title = NJDOT Graphic Information System Maps Middlesex |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation| |url = https://www.state.nj.us/transportation/gis/maps/monmouth.pdf |accessdate = March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt Locality Search], State of New Jersey. Accessed March 4, 2015.</ref> It was once known as '''Bethel'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=KxdoeHL0-1sC&pg=RA2-PA11&dq=abbot+creek+fairfield+cumberland+county+new+jersey&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwtO3Y-sPoAhW0wAIHHaW7AGgQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=abbot%20creek%20fairfield%20cumberland%20county%20new%20jersey&f=false|title=A Geographic Dictionary of New Jersey|first=Henry|last=Gannett|date=January 28, 1895|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = History of Howell Township |publisher = Howell Township |date = |url = https://www.twp.howell.nj.us/244/History-of-Howell-Township |accessdate = April 3, 2020| quote = The area was later called Turkey...before becoming known as Adelphia. In addition to Adelphia, Howell has a number of other early settlement areas that later became suburban neighborhoods: Bethel (Southard), Jerseyville (originally called Green Grove), Ramtown, Squankum, Freewood Acres, and Ardena. Bethel, an area in the southwest part of Howell Township, was settled in 1865 when a lot was donated by Israel Reynolds to build a Methodist Church that was completed in 1866. A school house opened in 1870, followed by a store in 1872. A post office opened in 1882 and reflected the area\u2019s name change from Bethel to Southard.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Monmouth County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Howell, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Monmouth County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{MonmouthCountyNJ-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Southard, New Jersey\n|settlement_type          = [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA New Jersey Monmouth County#USA New Jersey#USA\n|pushpin_label_position   = left\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location of Southard in Monmouth County Inset: Location of county within the state of New Jersey\n|pushpin_map1             =\n|pushpin_label_position1  =\n|pushpin_map_caption1     =\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|New Jersey}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in New Jersey|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Howell Township, New Jersey|Howell]]\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=GNIS/>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 118\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|08|18|N|74|13|30|W|region:US-NJ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info               = 880764<ref name=GNIS>{{cite gnis|880764|Southard}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref                = imperial\n}}\n'''Southard''' is an [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|unincorporated community]] located within [[Howell Township, New Jersey|Howell Township]] in [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth County]], [[New Jersey]], United States<ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt Locality Search], State of New Jersey. Accessed March 4, 2015.</ref> centered around [[U.S. Route 9 in New Jersey|U.S. Route 9]].<ref>{{cite web  |title = NJDOT Graphic Information System Maps Middlesex |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation| |url = https://www.state.nj.us/transportation/gis/maps/monmouth.pdf |accessdate = March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was once known as Bethel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=KxdoeHL0-1sC&pg=RA2-PA11&dq=abbot+creek+fairfield+cumberland+county+new+jersey&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwtO3Y-sPoAhW0wAIHHaW7AGgQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=abbot%20creek%20fairfield%20cumberland%20county%20new%20jersey&f=false|title=A Geographic Dictionary of New Jersey|first=Henry|last=Gannett|date=January 28, 1895|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = History of Howell Township |publisher = Howell Township |date = |url = https://www.twp.howell.nj.us/244/History-of-Howell-Township |accessdate = April 3, 2020| quote = The area was later called Turkey...before becoming known as Adelphia. In addition to Adelphia, Howell has a number of other early settlement areas that later became suburban neighborhoods: Bethel (Southard), Jerseyville (originally called Green Grove), Ramtown, Squankum, Freewood Acres, and Ardena. Bethel, an area in the southwest part of Howell Township, was settled in 1865 when a lot was donated by Israel Reynolds to build a Methodist Church that was completed in 1866. A school house opened in 1870, followed by a store in 1872. A post office opened in 1882 and reflected the area\u2019s name change from Bethel to Southard.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Monmouth County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Howell, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Monmouth County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{MonmouthCountyNJ-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tinton5", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southard,_New_Jersey"}
{"title_page": "Acquanetta", "text_new": "{{About|the American movie actress|the African-American dancer|Mildred Davenport}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = Acquanetta\n| image             = Aquanetta_image.jpg\n| caption           = Acquanetta in costume for ''{{nowrap|Tarzan and the Leopard Woman}}'', 1946.\n| birthname         = Mildred Davenport\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1921|7|17}}  \n| birth_place        = [[Newberry, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2004|8|16|1921|7|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Ahwatukee, Arizona]], U.S.\n| occupation        = Actress\n| yearsactive       = 1942\u20131953\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Luciano Bashuk|1948|1950|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Henry Clive]]|1950|1953|end=divorced}}<br>[[Jack Ross (Arizona)|Jack Ross]]<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 195?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 198?)\n| children          = 5\n}}\n'''Acquanetta''' (born '''Mildred Davenport'''; July 17, 1921 \u2013 August 16, 2004),{{efn|Some sources, including Social Security records, give her year of birth as ''1920''.<ref name=\"SSDI\">{{cite web |title=U.S., Social Security Applications and Claims Index, 1936-2007 |url=https://www.ancestry.com.au/inst/discoveries/PfRecord?emailId=N-b26a8013-1bc9-40f6-902c-7e54c01001f2&collectionId=60901&recordId=44399545&ahsht=2020-01-23T01:29:16&language=en-AU&ahsh=da3c9bf03a29a46e78280780e73460cc |website=Ancestry.com |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web |last1=Wollstein |first1=Hans J. |title=Acquanetta: Biography |url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/acquanetta-p211 |website=[[AllMovie]] |accessdate=23 January 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>}} nicknamed \"'''The Venezuelan Volcano''',\" was an American [[B movie|B-movie]] actress during the 1940s and 1950s. Acquanetta was most known for her exotic beauty.\n\n==Early years==\nThe facts of Acquanetta's origins are not known with certainty.<ref name=nt/><ref name=MS/><ref name=bg/> Although accounts differ (some giving her birth-name as Mildred Davenport, from [[Norristown, Pennsylvania]]),<ref name=nt>{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2004-09-02/culture/acqua-blues/|title=Acqua Blues|date=September 2, 2004|work=[[Phoenix New Times]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref><ref name=jf/><ref name=hjg>{{cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/2577937872/lightbox/|title=Hollywood Jungle Girl - The Actress Aquanetta|date=February 14, 1952|work=[[Jet Magazine]] |accessdate=July 6, 2013}}</ref> Acquanetta claimed she was born '''Burnu Acquanetta''', meaning \"Burning Fire/Deep Water\",<ref name=bg/> in Ozone, Wyoming. Orphaned from her [[Arapaho]] parents when she was two (or three),<ref name=\"LIFE-1942\" /> she lived briefly with another family before being taken in by an artistic couple with whom she remained until she made the choice to live independently at the age of fifteen.<ref name=MS>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kzUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3234,1835551&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|title=Billed As Venezuela Beauty,' Indian Girl Hoaxed Filmdom|date=July 20, 1942|work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312094603/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kzUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3234,1835551&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Other accounts suggest her ethnicity was [[African American]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=Freulich |first1=Roman |last2=Abramson |first2=Joan |title=Forty Years in Hollywood: Portraits of a Golden Age |date=1971 |publisher=Castle Books |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fortyyearsinholl00freu/page/73 73]-74 |url=https://archive.org/details/fortyyearsinholl00freu|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"Bojarski\">{{cite journal |last1=Bojarksi |first1=Richard |title=John Carradine, the Master Villain |journal=For Monsters Only |date=September 1971 |volume=1 |issue=9 |pages=52-53 |url=https://archive.org/details/For_Monsters_Only_v01n09_1971-09_Major_D/page/n45}}</ref> her career was followed closely by the African American press.<ref name=bg>{{cite web|url=http://vintageblackglamour.tumblr.com/post/3707146792/b-movie-star-acquanetta-although-she-was-promoted |title=B-movie star Acquanetta. Although she was promoted... - Vintage Black Glamour by Nichelle Gainer |website=Vintageblackglamour.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=hjg/>  In 1942, ''[[Life (magazine)|LIFE]]'' magazine noted her mysterious origins, but reported that she had lived with a Spanish family in [[Spanish Harlem]] posing as a Venezuelan before moving to Mexico, then Venezuela to obtain citizenship. The article suggests that the Arapaho orphan story was invented because she was unable to produce any identification for the [[Screen Actors Guild]].<ref name=\"LIFE-1942\">{{cite journal |title=Venezuelan Volcano |journal=LIFE |publisher=Time, Inc. |date=Aug 24, 1942 |volume=13 |issue=8 |pages=57\u201359 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fk4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&vq=Acquanetta&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=30 June 2018 |issn=0024-3019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 1940 [[US Census]], she had five siblings, including a sister, Kathryn Davenport,<ref name=jf/><ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/1217063237/ |title=Actress Acquanetta's Sister Marries in Tokyo - Jet Magazin\u2026 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> and a brother, Horace Davenport, who was, according to the [[Pennsylvania Bar Association]], \"the first African-American judge in [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]].\"<ref name=bg/><ref name=jf>{{cite web|author=Richard Beland |url=http://junglefrolics.blogspot.com/2009/10/acquanetta.html |title=Jungle Frolics: Acquanetta |website=Junglefrolics.blogspot.com |date=2009-10-15 |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |title=Horace Davenport, groundbreaking Montgomery County senior judge, dies at 98 |url=https://www.pottsmerc.com/news/horace-davenport-groundbreaking-montgomery-county-senior-judge-dies-at/article_95c904bf-4566-55c7-a229-9825aab84c70.html |work=The Pottstown Mercury |date=April 5, 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200123053846/https://www.pottsmerc.com/news/horace-davenport-groundbreaking-montgomery-county-senior-judge-dies-at/article_95c904bf-4566-55c7-a229-9825aab84c70.html |archivedate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\nAcquanetta started her career as a model in New York City<ref name=nt/><ref name=hjg/> with Harry Conover and [[John Robert Powers]].<ref name=jf/> She signed with [[Universal Studios]] in 1942 and acted mostly in B-movies, including ''[[Arabian Nights (1942 film)|Arabian Nights]]'', ''[[The Sword of Monte Cristo]]'', ''[[Captive Wild Woman]]'' and ''[[Jungle Woman]]'',<ref name=\"BC Times\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EWgyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K7UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4390,4777538&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|title=Acquanetta, Movie Actress|date=August 18, 2004|work=[[Beaver Country Times]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref> in which Universal attempted to create a female monster movie series with Acquanetta as a transformative ape. After her contract with Universal expired, Acquanetta signed on with [[Monogram Pictures]] but did not appear in any movies; she then signed with [[RKO]] where she acted in her only big-budget movie, ''[[Tarzan and the Leopard Woman]]''.<ref name=jf/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1947, Acquanetta and \"Mexican-Jewish millionaire\" Luciano Baschuk had a son, Sergei (variously Sergio), who died of cancer in 1952 at age five,<ref name=bg/><ref name=\"SB\">{{cite web |title=California, County Birth and Death Records, 1800-1994 |url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QG2Y-8K9K |website=FamilySearch |accessdate=10 February 2020|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/3035163739/ |title=Actress Acquanetta to Collect $4,000 in Son's Death - Jet \u2026 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> after the couple's bitter divorce in 1950,<ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/1298720031/ |title=Actress Acquanetta Has Child - Jet Magazine Aug 5, 1954 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> where she lost her suit for half his fortune when no record of their marriage could be produced.<ref name=bg/><ref name=jf/> In 1950, Acquanetta married painter and illustrator [[Henry Clive]], who was 40 years her senior, and returned to acting.<ref name=jf/><ref name=hjg/> The couple were divorced in 1953.<ref>{{cite news |title=Actress is Sued by Insurance Company |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38929758/acquanetta_wife_of_henry_clive_sued/ |work=Argus-Leader |date=March 15, 1953 |location=South Dakota|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> That same year she  retired from films and became a [[disk jockey]] for radio station [[KPOL (AM)]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=jf/>\n\nBy 1955 she had married [[Jack Ross (Arizona)|Jack Ross]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Acquanetta Wins Lawsuit Over Death of Her Son |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42709894/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=November 29, 1955 |pages=39|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stanley |first1=John |title=B-movie Star was A-list Arizonan |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42692939/ |work=Arizona Republic |date=April 7, 2013 |page=T2|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> a car dealer who later ran for governor of Arizona in [[Arizona gubernatorial election, 1970|1970]] and [[Arizona gubernatorial election, 1974|1974]]. The couple settled in [[Mesa, Arizona]],<ref name=RossObit>{{cite news |url=http://archive.azcentral.com/thingstodo/living/articles/20130215arizona-people-life-remembered-jack-ross.html |title=A Life Remembered: Jack Ross, iconic Arizona car dealer |last=Cone Sexton |first=Connie |work=[[The Arizona Republic]] |date=2013-02-15 |access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> and she returned to a degree of celebrity by appearing with Ross in his local television advertisements,<ref name=\"BC Times\"/> and also by hosting a local television show called ''Acqua's Corner'' that accompanied the Friday late-night movies.<ref name=jf/>  The couple were prominent citizens, donating to the [[Phoenix Symphony]] and the construction of Mesa Lutheran Hospital and founding Stagebrush Theatre.<ref name=nt/>  She and Ross had four sons together, Lance, Tom, Jack Jr. and Rex, before divorcing in the early 1980s. <ref name=RossObit/><ref>{{cite news |title=Acquanetta, Actress known as 'The Venezuelan Volcano' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/acquanetta-550306.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=August 19, 2004}}</ref> In 1987, Acquanetta sold the [[Mesa Grande]] ruins to the city of Mesa.<ref name=nt/> An apocryphal Phoenix legend has Acquanetta, upon learning of her husband's infidelity, filling the interior of his [[Lincoln Continental]] convertible with concrete.<ref name=nt/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2014-09-25/best-of-phoenix/legend-city-the-many-mysteries-of-acquanetta-and-jack-ross/full/|title=Best of Phoenix 2014: Legend City / The Many Mysteries of Acquanetta (and Jack Ross) |date=September 25, 2015|work=Phoenix New Times|accessdate=March 14, 2015}} </ref>\n\nAcquanetta also wrote a book of poetry, published in 1974, titled ''The Audible Silence''.<ref name=nt/><ref name=jf/><ref>{{cite book |author1=Acquanetta |author2=Illustrated by Emilie Touraine |title=The Audible Silence. |date=1974 |publisher=Northland Press |location=Flagstaff |isbn=9780873581196 |edition=1st}}</ref>She did not smoke, and did not drink alcohol, tea, or coffee.<ref name=jf/> In 1987, the [[all-female band]] [[The Aquanettas]] adopted (and adapted) their name from hers. Acquanetta succumbed to complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]] on August 16, 2004, at Hawthorn Court in [[Ahwatukee, Arizona]]. She was 83.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/23/arts/acquanetta-83-a-star-of-b-movies.html|title=Acquanetta, 83, A Star of B Movies|date=August 23, 2004|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref> Acquanetta's obituary inspired the composer [[Michael Gordon (composer)|Michael Gordon]] to collaborate with librettist Deborah Artman on the opera, ''Acquanetta'' (2005/2017). Produced by [[Beth Morrison|Beth Morrison Projects]], the chamber version received its world premiere at the [[Prototype Festival]] in Brooklyn, NY, in January, 2018.\n\n== Opera ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\n''Acquanetta'', based on her life,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brantley |first1=Ben |title=Review: In \u2018Acquanetta,\u2019 a Cult Movie Star\u2019s Eyes to Die For |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/14/theater/acquanetta-bard-summerscape-review.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=14 July 2019}}</ref> premiered as a [[Grand Opera]] in 2006 in Aachen, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |title=ACQUANETTA {{!}} Beth Morrison Projects |url=https://www.bethmorrisonprojects.org/acquanetta |website=bmp-opera-music |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The chamber version of ''Acquanetta'' had its world premiere at the 2018 [[Prototype Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquanetta|url=http://prototypefestival.org/shows/acquanetta/|website=Prototype Festival |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=9 January 2018}}</ref>, followed by a subsequent run at [[Bard SummerScape]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquanetta at Bard College |url=https://fishercenter.bard.edu/events/acquanetta/ |website=Fisher Center at Bard|accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1942\n| ''[[Arabian Nights (1942 film)|Arabian Nights]]''\n| Ishya\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1943\n| ''[[Rhythm of the Islands]]''\n| Luani\n| as Burnu Acquanetta\n|-\n| ''[[Captive Wild Woman]]''\n| Paula Dupree \u2013 the Gorilla Girl\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1944\n| ''[[Jungle Woman]]''\n| Paula Dupree \u2013 the Gorilla Girl\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Man's Eyes]]''\n| Tanya Czoraki\n|\n|-\n| 1946\n| ''[[Tarzan and the Leopard Woman]]''\n| Lea, the High Priestess\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1951\n| ''[[The Sword of Monte Cristo]]''\n| Felice\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Continent (1951 film)|Lost Continent]]''\n| Native Girl\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Callaway Went Thataway]]''\n| Native Girl with Smoky\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''[[Take the High Ground!]]''\n| Bar Girl\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Grizzly Adams \u2014 The Legend Never Dies''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mank |first1=Gregory William |title=Women in Horror Films, 1940s |date=2015 |publisher=McFarland & Co |isbn=9781476609553 |page=218 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n|\n| Direct-to-video release\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Price |first1=Michael H.|last2=Wooley |first2=John |authorlink2=John Wooley |title=Fantasies in the Sand: Birth of the Beach Party Box-Office Bonanza|date=3 September 2018  |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|location= |isbn=1723281069}} \u2014 Features Acquanetta and her connection to the [[beach party film]]s\n*\n\n==External links==\n*{{findagrave|9336496}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0010270|name=Acquanetta}}\n*{{Amg name|211}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acquanetta}}\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Native American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Wyoming]]\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Arapaho people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the American movie actress|the African-American dancer|Mildred Davenport}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = Acquanetta\n| image             = Aquanetta_image.jpg\n| caption           = Acquanetta in costume for ''{{nowrap|Tarzan and the Leopard Woman}}'', 1946.\n| birthname         = Mildred Davenport\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1921|7|17}}  \n| birth_place        = [[Newberry, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2004|8|16|1921|7|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Ahwatukee, Arizona]], U.S.\n| occupation        = Actress\n| yearsactive       = 1942\u20131953\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Luciano Bashuk|1948|1950|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Henry Clive]]|1950|1953|end=divorced}}<br>[[Jack Ross (Arizona)|Jack Ross]]<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 195?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 198?)\n| children          = 5\n}}\n'''Acquanetta''' (born '''Mildred Davenport'''; July 17, 1921 \u2013 August 16, 2004),{{efn|Some sources, including Social Security records, give her year of birth as ''1920''.<ref name=\"SSDI\">{{cite web |title=U.S., Social Security Applications and Claims Index, 1936-2007 |url=https://www.ancestry.com.au/inst/discoveries/PfRecord?emailId=N-b26a8013-1bc9-40f6-902c-7e54c01001f2&collectionId=60901&recordId=44399545&ahsht=2020-01-23T01:29:16&language=en-AU&ahsh=da3c9bf03a29a46e78280780e73460cc |website=Ancestry.com |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web |last1=Wollstein |first1=Hans J. |title=Acquanetta: Biography |url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/acquanetta-p211 |website=[[AllMovie]] |accessdate=23 January 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>}} nicknamed \"'''The Venezuelan Volcano''',\" was an American [[B movie|B-movie]] actress during the 1940s and 1950s. Acquanetta was most known for her exotic beauty.\n\n==Early years==\nThe facts of Acquanetta's origins are not known with certainty.<ref name=nt/><ref name=MS/><ref name=bg/> Although accounts differ (some giving her birth-name as Mildred Davenport, from [[Norristown, Pennsylvania]]),<ref name=nt>{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2004-09-02/culture/acqua-blues/|title=Acqua Blues|date=September 2, 2004|work=[[Phoenix New Times]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref><ref name=jf/><ref name=hjg>{{cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/2577937872/lightbox/|title=Hollywood Jungle Girl - The Actress Aquanetta|date=February 14, 1952|work=[[Jet Magazine]] |accessdate=July 6, 2013}}</ref> Acquanetta claimed she was born '''Burnu Acquanetta''', meaning \"Burning Fire/Deep Water\",<ref name=bg/> in Ozone, Wyoming. Orphaned from her [[Arapaho]] parents when she was two (or three),<ref name=\"LIFE-1942\" /> she lived briefly with another family before being taken in by an artistic couple with whom she remained until she made the choice to live independently at the age of fifteen.<ref name=MS>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kzUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3234,1835551&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|title=Billed As Venezuela Beauty,' Indian Girl Hoaxed Filmdom|date=July 20, 1942|work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312094603/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kzUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3234,1835551&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Other accounts suggest her ethnicity was [[African American]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=Freulich |first1=Roman |last2=Abramson |first2=Joan |title=Forty Years in Hollywood: Portraits of a Golden Age |date=1971 |publisher=Castle Books |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fortyyearsinholl00freu/page/73 73]-74 |url=https://archive.org/details/fortyyearsinholl00freu|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"Bojarski\">{{cite journal |last1=Bojarksi |first1=Richard |title=John Carradine, the Master Villain |journal=For Monsters Only |date=September 1971 |volume=1 |issue=9 |pages=52-53 |url=https://archive.org/details/For_Monsters_Only_v01n09_1971-09_Major_D/page/n45}}</ref> her career was followed closely by the African American press.<ref name=bg>{{cite web|url=http://vintageblackglamour.tumblr.com/post/3707146792/b-movie-star-acquanetta-although-she-was-promoted |title=B-movie star Acquanetta. Although she was promoted... - Vintage Black Glamour by Nichelle Gainer |website=Vintageblackglamour.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=hjg/>  In 1942, ''[[Life (magazine)|LIFE]]'' magazine noted her mysterious origins, but reported that she had lived with a Spanish family in [[Spanish Harlem]] posing as a Venezuelan before moving to Mexico, then Venezuela to obtain citizenship. The article suggests that the Arapaho orphan story was invented because she was unable to produce any identification for the [[Screen Actors Guild]].<ref name=\"LIFE-1942\">{{cite journal |title=Venezuelan Volcano |journal=LIFE |publisher=Time, Inc. |date=Aug 24, 1942 |volume=13 |issue=8 |pages=57\u201359 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fk4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&vq=Acquanetta&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=30 June 2018 |issn=0024-3019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 1940 [[US Census]], she had five siblings, including a sister, Kathryn Davenport,<ref name=jf/><ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/1217063237/ |title=Actress Acquanetta's Sister Marries in Tokyo - Jet Magazin\u2026 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> and a brother, Horace Davenport, who was, according to the [[Pennsylvania Bar Association]], \"the first African-American judge in [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]].\"<ref name=bg/><ref name=jf>{{cite web|author=Richard Beland |url=http://junglefrolics.blogspot.com/2009/10/acquanetta.html |title=Jungle Frolics: Acquanetta |website=Junglefrolics.blogspot.com |date=2009-10-15 |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |title=Horace Davenport, groundbreaking Montgomery County senior judge, dies at 98 |url=https://www.pottsmerc.com/news/horace-davenport-groundbreaking-montgomery-county-senior-judge-dies-at/article_95c904bf-4566-55c7-a229-9825aab84c70.html |work=The Pottstown Mercury |date=April 5, 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200123053846/https://www.pottsmerc.com/news/horace-davenport-groundbreaking-montgomery-county-senior-judge-dies-at/article_95c904bf-4566-55c7-a229-9825aab84c70.html |archivedate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\nAcquanetta started her career as a model in New York City<ref name=nt/><ref name=hjg/> with Harry Conover and [[John Robert Powers]].<ref name=jf/> She signed with [[Universal Studios]] in 1942 and acted mostly in B-movies, including ''[[Arabian Nights (1942 film)|Arabian Nights]]'', ''[[The Sword of Monte Cristo]]'', ''[[Captive Wild Woman]]'' and ''[[Jungle Woman]]'',<ref name=\"BC Times\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EWgyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K7UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4390,4777538&dq=acquanetta&hl=en|title=Acquanetta, Movie Actress|date=August 18, 2004|work=[[Beaver Country Times]]|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref> in which Universal attempted to create a female monster movie franchise with Acquanetta as a transformative ape. After her contract with Universal expired, Acquanetta signed on with [[Monogram Pictures]] but did not appear in any movies; she then signed with [[RKO]] where she acted in her only big-budget movie, ''[[Tarzan and the Leopard Woman]]''.<ref name=jf/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1947, Acquanetta and \"Mexican-Jewish millionaire\" Luciano Baschuk had a son, Sergei (variously Sergio), who died of cancer in 1952 at age five,<ref name=bg/><ref name=\"SB\">{{cite web |title=California, County Birth and Death Records, 1800-1994 |url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QG2Y-8K9K |website=FamilySearch |accessdate=10 February 2020|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/3035163739/ |title=Actress Acquanetta to Collect $4,000 in Son's Death - Jet \u2026 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> after the couple's bitter divorce in 1950,<ref>{{cite web|last=Annonces |first=Vieilles |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/1298720031/ |title=Actress Acquanetta Has Child - Jet Magazine Aug 5, 1954 |publisher=[[Flickr]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> where she lost her suit for half his fortune when no record of their marriage could be produced.<ref name=bg/><ref name=jf/> In 1950, Acquanetta married painter and illustrator [[Henry Clive]], who was 40 years her senior, and returned to acting.<ref name=jf/><ref name=hjg/> The couple were divorced in 1953.<ref>{{cite news |title=Actress is Sued by Insurance Company |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38929758/acquanetta_wife_of_henry_clive_sued/ |work=Argus-Leader |date=March 15, 1953 |location=South Dakota|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> That same year she  retired from films and became a [[disk jockey]] for radio station [[KPOL (AM)]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=jf/>\n\nBy 1955 she had married [[Jack Ross (Arizona)|Jack Ross]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Acquanetta Wins Lawsuit Over Death of Her Son |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42709894/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=November 29, 1955 |pages=39|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stanley |first1=John |title=B-movie Star was A-list Arizonan |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42692939/ |work=Arizona Republic |date=April 7, 2013 |page=T2|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> a car dealer who later ran for governor of Arizona in [[Arizona gubernatorial election, 1970|1970]] and [[Arizona gubernatorial election, 1974|1974]]. The couple settled in [[Mesa, Arizona]],<ref name=RossObit>{{cite news |url=http://archive.azcentral.com/thingstodo/living/articles/20130215arizona-people-life-remembered-jack-ross.html |title=A Life Remembered: Jack Ross, iconic Arizona car dealer |last=Cone Sexton |first=Connie |work=[[The Arizona Republic]] |date=2013-02-15 |access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> and she returned to a degree of celebrity by appearing with Ross in his local television advertisements,<ref name=\"BC Times\"/> and also by hosting a local television show called ''Acqua's Corner'' that accompanied the Friday late-night movies.<ref name=jf/>  The couple were prominent citizens, donating to the [[Phoenix Symphony]] and the construction of Mesa Lutheran Hospital and founding Stagebrush Theatre.<ref name=nt/>  She and Ross had four sons together, Lance, Tom, Jack Jr. and Rex, before divorcing in the early 1980s. <ref name=RossObit/><ref>{{cite news |title=Acquanetta, Actress known as 'The Venezuelan Volcano' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/acquanetta-550306.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=August 19, 2004}}</ref> In 1987, Acquanetta sold the [[Mesa Grande]] ruins to the city of Mesa.<ref name=nt/> An apocryphal Phoenix legend has Acquanetta, upon learning of her husband's infidelity, filling the interior of his [[Lincoln Continental]] convertible with concrete.<ref name=nt/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2014-09-25/best-of-phoenix/legend-city-the-many-mysteries-of-acquanetta-and-jack-ross/full/|title=Best of Phoenix 2014: Legend City / The Many Mysteries of Acquanetta (and Jack Ross) |date=September 25, 2015|work=Phoenix New Times|accessdate=March 14, 2015}} </ref>\n\nAcquanetta also wrote a book of poetry, published in 1974, titled ''The Audible Silence''.<ref name=nt/><ref name=jf/><ref>{{cite book |author1=Acquanetta |author2=Illustrated by Emilie Touraine |title=The Audible Silence. |date=1974 |publisher=Northland Press |location=Flagstaff |isbn=9780873581196 |edition=1st}}</ref>She did not smoke, and did not drink alcohol, tea, or coffee.<ref name=jf/> In 1987, the [[all-female band]] [[The Aquanettas]] adopted (and adapted) their name from hers. Acquanetta succumbed to complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]] on August 16, 2004, at Hawthorn Court in [[Ahwatukee, Arizona]]. She was 83.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/23/arts/acquanetta-83-a-star-of-b-movies.html|title=Acquanetta, 83, A Star of B Movies|date=August 23, 2004|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref> Acquanetta's obituary inspired the composer [[Michael Gordon (composer)|Michael Gordon]] to collaborate with librettist Deborah Artman on the opera, ''Acquanetta'' (2005/2017). Produced by [[Beth Morrison|Beth Morrison Projects]], the chamber version received its world premiere at the [[Prototype Festival]] in Brooklyn, NY, in January, 2018.\n\n== Opera ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\n''Acquanetta'', based on her life,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brantley |first1=Ben |title=Review: In \u2018Acquanetta,\u2019 a Cult Movie Star\u2019s Eyes to Die For |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/14/theater/acquanetta-bard-summerscape-review.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=14 July 2019}}</ref> premiered as a [[Grand Opera]] in 2006 in Aachen, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |title=ACQUANETTA {{!}} Beth Morrison Projects |url=https://www.bethmorrisonprojects.org/acquanetta |website=bmp-opera-music |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The chamber version of ''Acquanetta'' had its world premiere at the 2018 [[Prototype Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquanetta|url=http://prototypefestival.org/shows/acquanetta/|website=Prototype Festival |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=9 January 2018}}</ref>, followed by a subsequent run at [[Bard SummerScape]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquanetta at Bard College |url=https://fishercenter.bard.edu/events/acquanetta/ |website=Fisher Center at Bard|accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1942\n| ''[[Arabian Nights (1942 film)|Arabian Nights]]''\n| Ishya\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1943\n| ''[[Rhythm of the Islands]]''\n| Luani\n| as Burnu Acquanetta\n|-\n| ''[[Captive Wild Woman]]''\n| Paula Dupree \u2013 the Gorilla Girl\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1944\n| ''[[Jungle Woman]]''\n| Paula Dupree \u2013 the Gorilla Girl\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Man's Eyes]]''\n| Tanya Czoraki\n|\n|-\n| 1946\n| ''[[Tarzan and the Leopard Woman]]''\n| Lea, the High Priestess\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1951\n| ''[[The Sword of Monte Cristo]]''\n| Felice\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Continent (1951 film)|Lost Continent]]''\n| Native Girl\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Callaway Went Thataway]]''\n| Native Girl with Smoky\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''[[Take the High Ground!]]''\n| Bar Girl\n| (uncredited)\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Grizzly Adams \u2014 The Legend Never Dies''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mank |first1=Gregory William |title=Women in Horror Films, 1940s |date=2015 |publisher=McFarland & Co |isbn=9781476609553 |page=218 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n|\n| Direct-to-video release\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Price |first1=Michael H.|last2=Wooley |first2=John |authorlink2=John Wooley |title=Fantasies in the Sand: Birth of the Beach Party Box-Office Bonanza|date=3 September 2018  |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|location= |isbn=1723281069}} \u2014 Features Acquanetta and her connection to the [[beach party film]]s\n*\n\n==External links==\n*{{findagrave|9336496}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0010270|name=Acquanetta}}\n*{{Amg name|211}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acquanetta}}\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Native American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Wyoming]]\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Arapaho people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n", "name_user": "Chips Critic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected anachronistic terminology.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acquanetta"}
{"title_page": "W. Patterson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = W. Patterson\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     =\n| birth_place    = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| years1         = 1891\u20131892\n| clubs1         = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps1          = 4\n| goals1         = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n}}'''W. H. Patterson''' (date of birth unknown) was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]] who played in [[The Football League]] for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] between 1891 and 1892.<ref name=\"blades whos who\">{{cite book |author=Denis Clarebrough & Andrew Kirkham |title=Sheffield United Who's Who |publisher=Hallamshire Press |year=2008|page=252 |isbn=978-1-874718-69-7}}</ref> Primarily a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] he also filled in on various positions during his time at [[Bramall Lane]].<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n\nPatterson (or ''Pattison'' as he was referred to on occasions)<ref name=\"blades whos who\" /> was simply described as being \"from [[Edinburgh]]\" by the local press on his signing by United in December 1891.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />  He featured only irregularly in the first team and played just a handful of competitive games.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />  By 1892 and with United now in [[The Football League]] more first team chances looked beyond him and it was announced he had left the club by December of that year.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patterson, W.}}\n[[Category:Footballers from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Northern Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = W. Patterson\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Unknown\n| birth_date     = Unknown\n| birth_place    = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n| death_date     = Unknown\n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| years1         = 1891\u20131892\n| clubs1         = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps1          = 4\n| goals1         = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n}}'''W. H. Patterson''' (date of birth unknown) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Association football|footballer]] who played in [[The Football League]] for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] between 1891 and 1892.<ref name=\"blades whos who\">{{cite book |author=Denis Clarebrough & Andrew Kirkham |title=Sheffield United Who's Who |publisher=Hallamshire Press |year=2008|page=252 |isbn=978-1-874718-69-7}}</ref>  Primarily a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] he also filled in on various positions during his time at [[Bramall Lane]].<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n\nPatterson (or ''Pattison'' as he was referred to on occasions)<ref name=\"blades whos who\" /> was simply described as being \"from [[Edinburgh]]\" by the local press on his signing by United in December 1891.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />  He featured only irregularly in the first team and played just a handful of competitive games.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />  By 1892 and with United now in [[The Football League]] more first team chances looked beyond him and it was announced he had left the club by December of that year.<ref name=\"blades whos who\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patterson, W.}}\n[[Category:Footballers from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Northern Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Patterson"}
{"title_page": "Shamim Azad", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Shamim Azad\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = S. azad.jpg\n\n| image_size    = 220px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \u09b6\u09be\u09ae\u09c0\u09ae \u0986\u099c\u09be\u09a6\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = Shamim Azad\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1952|11|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Mymensingh]], [[Dhaka]], [[East Bengal]] (now [[Bangladesh]])\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Poet, storyteller, writer\n| language      = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], English\n| nationality   = Bangladeshi\n| citizenship   = British\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Kumudini College]]<br />[[Dhaka University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| awards        = \n| years_active  = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| parents    = Abu Ahmad Mahmud Tarafdar (father)<br />Anowara Khanom (mother)\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Shamim Azad''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09be\u09ae\u09c0\u09ae \u0986\u099c\u09be\u09a6}}; born 11 November 1952)<ref name=\"bsklondon\">{{cite web|url=http://bsklondon.co.uk/upcomingevents.aspx/|title=World Literature Centre, London|date=11 November 2011|accessdate=23 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103023459/http://bsklondon.co.uk/upcomingevents.aspx|archivedate=3 January 2012|df=dmy-all}} Upcoming Events</ref> is a Bangladeshi-born British [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] poet, storyteller and writer.\n\n==Early life==\nAzad was born in [[Mymensingh]], [[Dhaka]], [[East Bengal]] (now [[Bangladesh]]) (the town where her father worked), her hometown was [[Sylhet]]. She passed her Metric from [[Jamalpur District|Jamalpur]] Girls High School in 1967 and passed her Intermediate from [[Tangail]] [[Kumudini College]] in 1969. She enrolled in [[Dhaka University]] and gained an [[Honours degree]] in 1972 and a master's degree in 1973.<ref name=\"banglanews24\">{{cite news|url=http://www.banglanews24.com/English/detailsnews.php?nssl=070151fbdb4fa874242f4d03fe75c57c&nttl=2012032833946|title=Shamim Azad's birthday to be celebrated in Dhaka|work=banglanews24|date=22 February 2012|accessdate=1 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227092314/http://www.banglanews24.com/English/detailsnews.php?nssl=070151fbdb4fa874242f4d03fe75c57c&nttl=2012032833946|archivedate=27 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Azad came to England.<ref name=\"poetrymagazines\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poetrymagazines.org.uk/magazine/record.asp?id=12677|title=Biographical notes \u2013 The Poets|publisher=Poetry Magazines|year=2001|pages=293\u2013305|accessdate=23 January 2012}} Shamim Azad</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAzad's work ranges from Bangladeshi to European folktales. Her performance fuses the lines between education and entertainment and her workshops are rooted in Asian folk, oral traditions and heritage.<ref name=\"poetrysociety\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/info/npd/history/npd05/london/|title=Poetry and Translation|location=London|publisher=The Poetry Society|date= |accessdate=23 September 2011}} The Poets: Shamim Azad</ref>\n\nAzad has published 35 books<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/images/whos-who-2013.pdf|date=October 2013|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=62|isbn= |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> including novels, collections of short stories, essays and poems in both English and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and has been included in various anthologies including ''British South Asian Poetry'', ''My Birth Was Not in Vain'', ''Velocity'',''Emlit Project'' and ''Mother Tongues''. She wrote two plays for [[Half Moon Theatre]].<ref name=\"bbwhoswho09\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/whoswho_09.pdf|date=October 2009|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=33|isbn= |accessdate=24 September 2011}}</ref> She has worked with composers [[Richard Blackford]], [[Kerry Andrew]], choreographer Rosemary Lee, visual artist Robin Whitemore and playwright Mary Cooper.<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\"/>\n\nShe has performed at venues including the [[Museum of London]], Edinburgh Fringe Festival, Cambridge Water Stone, [[Liberty Radio]], [[Battersea Arts Centre]], [[Lauderdale House]], the [[Commonwealth Institute]], [[British Library]], British Council of Bangladesh, Takshila in Pakistan and New York.<ref name=\"thedailystar\">{{cite news |last=Mahboob|first=Mahdin|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/campus/2007/08/02/feature_BRAC.htm|title=Creative Writing Workshop @ BRAC University by Shamim Azad|location= |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=12 August 2007|accessdate=24 September 2011}} Volume 2, Issue 31</ref> Her residencies have included, [[Tower Hamlets Summer University]], Sunderland City Library and Arts Centre, East Side Arts, [[Poetry Society]], Magic Me, [[Rich Mix Cultural Foundation|Rich Mix]], Kinetika, [[Bromley by Bow Centre]], Half Moon Theatre, and [[Apples and Snakes]].<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\"/>\n\nAzad is a trustee of charity [[One World Action]] and Rich Mix in [[Bethnal Green]], London. She is a school governor and chairperson of [[Bishwo Shahitto Kendro]] (World Literature Centre) in London.<ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> She is part of the East storytelling group, which invites local residents to join in sharing some of the stories brought together by the Eastend's rich, diverse history of immigration.<ref name=\"daedalustheatre\">{{cite web |url=http://www.daedalustheatre.co.uk/east.html|title=East|publisher=[[BBC Asian Network]]|date=16 November 2013|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAzad received the Bangladesh \"Bichitra Award\" in 1994, \"Year of the Artist\" Award from [[London Arts]] in 2000, \"Sonjojon- A Rouf\" Award in 2004, and UK \"Civic Award\" in 2004. Community Champions Award in 2014 by Canary Wharf group PLC.<ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> In 2016, she was awarded \"[[Syed Waliullah]] Literature Award\"2016, which is conferred by the [[Bangla Academy]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAzad lives in [[Wanstead]], [[London Borough of Redbridge|Redbridge]], London.<ref name=\"towerhamletsarts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.towerhamletsarts.org.uk/?cat=29&cid=29116&guide=Artists|title=Shamim Azad \u2013 Artists directory|publisher=Tower Hamlets Arts & Entertainment|date= |accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Novel and stories===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1988\n| ''Shirno Shuktara''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1989\n| ''Dui Romonir Moddhoshomoy''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1991\n| ''Arekjon''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2003\n| ''Shamim Azader Golpo Shonkolon''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2009\n| ''A Vocal Chorus''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2012\n| ''Priongboda''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| ''Bongshobeej''\n|}\n\n===Poetry===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1983\n| ''Valobashar Kobita''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1984\n| ''Sporsher Opekkha''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1988\n| ''He Jubok Tomar Vobisshot''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2007\n| ''Om''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| ''Jiol Jokhom''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2010\n| ''Jonmandho Jupiter''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2011\n| ''Shamim Azader Prem Opremer 100 Kobita''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Children's literature and drama===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1992\n| ''Hopscotch Ghost'' (with Mary Cooper)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1994\n| ''The Raft''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2000\n| ''The Life of Mr. Aziz''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2012\n| ''Boogly The Burgundy Cheetah''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Poetry collections and translations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1998\n| ''British South Asian Poetry''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2001\n| ''My Birth Was Not in Vain''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2003\n| ''Velocity'' (''25 Bochorer Bileter Kobita'')\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| ''The Majestic Night''\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[British Bangladeshi]]\n* [[Performance poetry]]\n* [[List of British Bangladeshis]]\n* [[List of Bengali poets]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[List of English writers]]\n* [[List of Muslim writers and poets]]\n* [[List of performance poets]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* Mahboob, Mahdin. [http://dspace.bracu.ac.bd/bitstream/handle/10361/1299/12.08.07%20Star%20Campus.pdf?sequence=1 Creative Writing Workshop @ BRAC University by Shamim Azad]. ''Star Campus'' (''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]''), Volume 2, Issue 31, 12 August 2007\n* Kvist, Elsie. [http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/news/author_shamim_azad_helps_children_mark_the_end_of_london_games_at_three_mills_in_bromley_by_bow_1_1511113 Author Shamim Azad helps children mark the end of London Games at Three Mills in Bromley-by-bow]. ''[[Docklands and East London Advertiser|East London Advertiser]]''. 10 September 2012\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azad, Shamim}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British writers]]\n[[Category:British Muslims]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:British women novelists]]\n[[Category:British people of Bangladeshi descent]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi women writers]]\n[[Category:British Asian writers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi women poets]]\n[[Category:British women poets]]\n[[Category:Muslim poets]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language poets]]\n[[Category:English-language poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:People from Mymensingh District]]\n[[Category:People from Wanstead]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Shamim Azad\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = S. azad.jpg\n\n| image_size    = 220px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \u09b6\u09be\u09ae\u09c0\u09ae \u0986\u099c\u09be\u09a6\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = Shamim Azad\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1952|11|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Mymensingh]], [[Dhaka]], [[East Bengal]] (now [[Bangladesh]])\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Poet, storyteller, writer\n| language      = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], English\n| nationality   = Bangladeshi\n| citizenship   = British\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Kumudini College]]<br />[[Dhaka University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| awards        = \n| years_active  = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| parents    = Abu Ahmad Mahmud Tarafdar (father)<br />Anowara Khanom (mother)\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Shamim Azad''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09be\u09ae\u09c0\u09ae \u0986\u099c\u09be\u09a6}}; born 11 November 1952)<ref name=\"bsklondon\">{{cite web|url=http://bsklondon.co.uk/upcomingevents.aspx/|title=World Literature Centre, London|date=11 November 2011|accessdate=23 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103023459/http://bsklondon.co.uk/upcomingevents.aspx|archivedate=3 January 2012|df=dmy-all}} Upcoming Events</ref> is a Bangladeshi-born British [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] poet, storyteller and writer.\n\n==Early life==\nAzad was born in [[Mymensingh]], [[Dhaka]], [[East Bengal]] (now [[Bangladesh]]) (the town where her father worked), her hometown was [[Sylhet]]. She passed her Metric from [[Jamalpur District|Jamalpur]] Girls High School in 1967 and passed her Intermediate from [[Tangail]] [[Kumudini College]] in 1969. She enrolled in [[Dhaka University]] and gained an [[Honours degree]] in 1972 and a master's degree in 1973.<ref name=\"banglanews24\">{{cite news|url=http://www.banglanews24.com/English/detailsnews.php?nssl=070151fbdb4fa874242f4d03fe75c57c&nttl=2012032833946|title=Shamim Azad's birthday to be celebrated in Dhaka|work=banglanews24|date=22 February 2012|accessdate=1 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227092314/http://www.banglanews24.com/English/detailsnews.php?nssl=070151fbdb4fa874242f4d03fe75c57c&nttl=2012032833946|archivedate=27 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Azad came to England.<ref name=\"poetrymagazines\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poetrymagazines.org.uk/magazine/record.asp?id=12677|title=Biographical notes \u2013 The Poets|publisher=Poetry Magazines|year=2001|pages=293\u2013305|accessdate=23 January 2012}} Shamim Azad</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAzad's work ranges from Bangladeshi to European folktales. Her performance fuses the lines between education and entertainment and her workshops are rooted in Asian folk, oral traditions and heritage.<ref name=\"poetrysociety\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/info/npd/history/npd05/london/|title=Poetry and Translation|location=London|publisher=The Poetry Society|date= |accessdate=23 September 2011}} The Poets: Shamim Azad</ref>\n\nAzad has published 35 books<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/images/whos-who-2013.pdf|date=October 2013|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=62|isbn= |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> including novels, collections of short stories, essays and poems in both English and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and has been included in various anthologies including ''British South Asian Poetry'', ''My Birth Was Not in Vain'', ''Velocity'',''Emlit Project'' and ''Mother Tongues''. She wrote two plays for [[Half Moon Theatre]].<ref name=\"bbwhoswho09\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/whoswho_09.pdf|date=October 2009|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=33|isbn= |accessdate=24 September 2011}}</ref> She has worked with composers [[Richard Blackford]], [[Kerry Andrew]], choreographer Rosemary Lee, visual artist Robin Whitemore and playwright Mary Cooper.<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\"/>\n\nShe has performed at venues including the [[Museum of London]],Edinburgh Fringe Festival, Cambridge Water Stone, [[Liberty Radio]], [[Battersea Arts Centre]], [[Lauderdale House]], the [[Commonwealth Institute]], [[British Library]], British Council of Bangladesh, Takshila in Pakistan and New York.<ref name=\"thedailystar\">{{cite news |last=Mahboob|first=Mahdin|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/campus/2007/08/02/feature_BRAC.htm|title=Creative Writing Workshop @ BRAC University by Shamim Azad|location= |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=12 August 2007|accessdate=24 September 2011}} Volume 2, Issue 31</ref> Her residencies have included, [[Tower Hamlets Summer University]], Sunderland City Library and Arts Centre, East Side Arts, [[Poetry Society]], Magic Me, [[Rich Mix Cultural Foundation|Rich Mix]], Kinetika, [[Bromley by Bow Centre]], Half Moon Theatre, and [[Apples and Snakes]].<ref name=\"bbwhoswho13\"/>\n\nAzad is a trustee of charity [[One World Action]] and Rich Mix in [[Bethnal Green]], London. She is a school governor and chairperson of [[Bishwo Shahitto Kendro]] (World Literature Centre) in London.<ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> She is part of the East storytelling group, which invites local residents to join in sharing some of the stories brought together by the Eastend's rich, diverse history of immigration.<ref name=\"daedalustheatre\">{{cite web |url=http://www.daedalustheatre.co.uk/east.html|title=East|publisher=[[BBC Asian Network]]|date=16 November 2013|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAzad received the Bangladesh \"Bichitra Award\" in 1994, \"Year of the Artist\" Award from [[London Arts]] in 2000, \"Sonjojon- A Rouf\" Award in 2004, and UK \"Civic Award\" in 2004. Community Champions Award in 2014 by Canary Wharf group PLC. <ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> In 2016, she was awarded \"[[Syed Waliullah]] Literature Award\"2016, which is conferred by the [[Bangla Academy]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAzad lives in [[Wanstead]], [[London Borough of Redbridge|Redbridge]], London.<ref name=\"towerhamletsarts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.towerhamletsarts.org.uk/?cat=29&cid=29116&guide=Artists|title=Shamim Azad \u2013 Artists directory|publisher=Tower Hamlets Arts & Entertainment|date= |accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Novel and stories===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1988\n| ''Shirno Shuktara''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1989\n| ''Dui Romonir Moddhoshomoy''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1991\n| ''Arekjon''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2003\n| ''Shamim Azader Golpo Shonkolon''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2009\n| ''A Vocal Chorus''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2012\n| ''Priongboda''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| ''Bongshobeej''\n|}\n===Poetry===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1983\n| ''Valobashar Kobita''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1984\n| ''Sporsher Opekkha''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1988\n| ''He Jubok Tomar Vobisshot''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2007\n| ''Om''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| ''Jiol Jokhom''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2010\n| ''Jonmandho Jupiter''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2011\n| ''Shamim Azader Prem Opremer 100 Kobita''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Children's literature and drama===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1992\n| ''Hopscotch Ghost'' (with Mary Cooper)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1994\n| ''The Raft''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2000\n| ''The Life of Mr. Aziz''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2012\n| ''Boogly The Burgundy Cheetah''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Poetry collections and translations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1998\n| ''British South Asian Poetry''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2001\n| ''My Birth Was Not in Vain''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2003\n| ''Velocity'' (''25 Bochorer Bileter Kobita'')\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| ''The Majestic Night''\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[British Bangladeshi]]\n* [[Performance poetry]]\n* [[List of British Bangladeshis]]\n* [[List of Bengali poets]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[List of English writers]]\n* [[List of Muslim writers and poets]]\n* [[List of performance poets]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* Mahboob, Mahdin. [http://dspace.bracu.ac.bd/bitstream/handle/10361/1299/12.08.07%20Star%20Campus.pdf?sequence=1 Creative Writing Workshop @ BRAC University by Shamim Azad]. ''Star Campus'' (''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]''), Volume 2, Issue 31, 12 August 2007\n* Kvist, Elsie. [http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/news/author_shamim_azad_helps_children_mark_the_end_of_london_games_at_three_mills_in_bromley_by_bow_1_1511113 Author Shamim Azad helps children mark the end of London Games at Three Mills in Bromley-by-bow]. ''[[Docklands and East London Advertiser|