{"title_page": "Wally Bragg", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Wally Bragg\n| image       = \n| fullname    = Walter Leonard Bragg<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|2089|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=y|1929|7|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Twickenham]], England\n| death_date  ={{death date and age|2016|3|6|1929|7|8|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| death_place = Twickenham, England\n| position    = [[Centre half]]\n|youthyears1 = \n|youthclubs1 = Twickenham Celtic\n| years1 = 1946\u20131957  \n| clubs1 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]  \n| caps1 = 161   \n| goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 1946\u20131947\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Hounslow Town F.C.|Hounslow Town]] (loan)  \n| caps2 =    \n| goals2 = \n}}\n'''Walter Leonard Bragg''' (8 July 1929 \u2013 6 March 2016) was an English professional [[Association football|football]] [[centre half]] who played in [[the Football League]] for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. At the time of his debut in March 1947, he was Brentford's then-youngest first team debutant.\n\n== Career ==\nAn amateur [[centre half]], Bragg joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in early 1946 from local team Twickenham Celtic.<ref name=\"YoungPivot\">{{Cite news |title=Young Pivot |date=10 January 1947 |work=The Brentford & Chiswick Times}}</ref> After a spell out on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Corinthian League (football)|Corinthian League]] club [[Hounslow Town F.C.|Hounslow Town]], he turned professional in January 1947.<ref name=\"YoungPivot\" /> He made his debut at [[outside right]], in place of [[Idris Hopkins]] for the visit of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on 29 March 1947 and his appearance in the 1\u20130 defeat made him Brentford's youngest debutant at that time.<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{Cite book|title=Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920\u20132006|last=Haynes|first=Graham|last2=Coumbe|first2=Frank|publisher=Yore Publications|year=2006|isbn=978-0955294914|location=|pages=25\u201326}}</ref> A call-up for [[National Service in the United Kingdom|national service]] saw him fail to appear again until the second half of the [[1951\u201352 Brentford F.C. season|1951\u201352]] [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] season,<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> when he enjoyed a run of 10 appearances.{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}} He then went on to become a regular fixture in the team through the mid-1950s and made a career-high 44 appearances during a disastrous [[1953\u201354 Brentford F.C. season|1953\u201354]] season, in which the Bees were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]].{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}<ref>{{Fchd|id=BRENTFOR|name=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> Bragg played on until the end of the [[1956\u201357 Brentford F.C. season|1956\u201357]] season, when he retired from football after a succession of injuries.<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> He was posthumously inducted into the club's [[Brentford F.C. Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] in May 2018.<ref name=\"halloffame\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/may/2018-player-of-the-year-award-winners/ |title=Prizes shared at last night's Player of the Year Awards |accessdate=7 May 2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrior to becoming a professional footballer, Bragg worked as a [[linotype operator]] for a printing firm in [[Richmond, London|Richmond]].<ref name=\"YoungPivot\" /> He served his national service in the [[RAF]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> After retiring from football, he worked as an advertising manager for local newspapers in [[Twickenham]].<ref name=\"Brett\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.brentfordfc.co.uk/news/article/former-brentford-player-walter-bradd-dies-2999146.aspx |title=Walter Bragg, Brentford's last surviving member of our Division One side, dies aged 86 |last=Brett |first=Ciaran |website=www.brentfordfc.co.uk |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> He was married with a son and two daughters and five grandchildren and at the time of his death in March 2016.<ref name=\"Brett\" />\n\n== Honours ==\n\n* [[Brentford F.C. Hall of Fame|Brentford Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"halloffame\" />\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" |[[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Brentford F.C. season|1946\u201347]]<ref>{{Cite book |title=100 Years Of Brentford |publisher=Brentford FC |year=1989 |isbn=0951526200 |editor-last=White |editor-first=Eric |page=378}}</ref>\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[1951\u201352 Brentford F.C. season|1951\u201352]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|10\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|10\n|1\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Brentford F.C. season|1952\u201353]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|38\n|0\n|3\n|0\n|41\n|0\n|-\n|[[1953\u201354 Brentford F.C. season|1953\u201354]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|41\n|1\n|3\n|0\n|44\n|1\n|-\n|[[1954\u201355 Brentford F.C. season|1954\u201355]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]]\n|9\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|9\n|0\n|-\n|[[1955\u201356 Brentford F.C. season|1955\u201356]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|29\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|29\n|2\n|-\n|[[1956\u201357 Brentford F.C. season|1956\u201357]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|33\n|2\n|1\n|0\n|34\n|2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!161!!6!!7!!0!!168!!6\n|}\n\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player7/wallybragg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}{{Brentford F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bragg, Wally}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hounslow F.C. players]]\n[[Category:20th-century Royal Air Force personnel]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Twickenham]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force airmen]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Wally Bragg\n| image       = \n| fullname    = Walter Leonard Bragg<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|2089|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=y|1929|7|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Twickenham]], England\n| death_date  ={{death date and age|2016|3|6|1929|7|8|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| death_place = Twickenham, England\n| position    = [[Centre half]]\n|youthyears1 = \n|youthclubs1 = Twickenham Celtic\n| years1 = 1946\u20131957  \n| clubs1 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]  \n| caps1 = 161   \n| goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 1946\u20131947\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Hounslow Town F.C.|Hounslow Town]] (loan)  \n| caps2 =    \n| goals2 = \n}}\n'''Walter Leonard Bragg''' (8 July 1929 \u2013 6 March 2016) was an English professional [[Association football|football]] [[centre half]] who played in [[the Football League]] for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. At the time of his debut in March 1947, he was Brentford's then-youngest first team debutant.\n\n== Career ==\nAn amateur [[centre half]], Bragg joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in early 1946 from local team Twickenham Celtic.<ref name=\"YoungPivot\">{{Cite news |title=Young Pivot |date=10 January 1947 |work=The Brentford & Chiswick Times}}</ref> After a spell out on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Corinthian League (football)|Corinthian League]] club [[Hounslow Town F.C.|Hounslow Town]], he turned professional in January 1947.<ref name=\"YoungPivot\" /> He made his debut at [[outside right]], in place of [[Idris Hopkins]] for the visit of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on 29 March 1947 and his appearance in the 1\u20130 defeat made him Brentford's youngest debutant at that time.<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{Cite book|title=Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920\u20132006|last=Haynes|first=Graham|last2=Coumbe|first2=Frank|publisher=Yore Publications|year=2006|isbn=978-0955294914|location=|pages=25\u201326}}</ref> A call-up for [[National Service in the United Kingdom|national service]] saw him fail to appear again until the second half of the [[1951\u201352 Brentford F.C. season|1951\u201352]] [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] season,<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> when he enjoyed a run of 10 appearances.{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}} He then went on to become a regular fixture in the team through the mid-1950s and made a career-high 44 appearances during a disastrous [[1953\u201354 Brentford F.C. season|1953\u201354]] season, in which the Bees were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]].{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}<ref>{{Fchd|id=BRENTFOR|name=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> Bragg played on until the end of the [[1956\u201357 Brentford F.C. season|1956\u201357]] season, when he retired from football after a succession of injuries.<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> He was posthumously inducted into the club's [[Brentford F.C. Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] in May 2018.<ref name=\"halloffame\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/may/2018-player-of-the-year-award-winners/ |title=Prizes shared at last night's Player of the Year Awards |accessdate=7 May 2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrior to becoming a professional footballer, Bragg worked as a [[linotype operator]] for a printing firm in [[Richmond, London|Richmond]].<ref name=\"YoungPivot\" /> He served his national service in the [[RAF]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> After retiring from football, he worked as an advertising manager for local newspapers in [[Twickenham]].<ref name=\"Brett\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.brentfordfc.co.uk/news/article/former-brentford-player-walter-bradd-dies-2999146.aspx |title=Walter Bragg, Brentford's last surviving member of our Division One side, dies aged 86 |last=Brett |first=Ciaran |website=www.brentfordfc.co.uk |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> He was married with a son and two daughters and five grandchildren and at the time of his death in March 2016.<ref name=\"Brett\" />\n\n== Honours ==\n\n* [[Brentford F.C. Hall of Fame|Brentford Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"halloffame\" />\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" |[[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Brentford F.C. season|1946\u201347]]<ref>{{Cite book |title=100 Years Of Brentford |publisher=Brentford FC |year=1989 |isbn=0951526200 |editor-last=White |editor-first=Eric |page=378}}</ref>\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[1951\u201352 Brentford F.C. season|1951\u201352]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|10\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|10\n|1\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Brentford F.C. season|1952\u201353]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|38\n|0\n|3\n|0\n|41\n|0\n|-\n|[[1953\u201354 Brentford F.C. season|1953\u201354]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|41\n|1\n|3\n|0\n|44\n|1\n|-\n|[[1954\u201355 Brentford F.C. season|1954\u201355]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]]\n|9\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|9\n|0\n|-\n|[[1955\u201356 Brentford F.C. season|1955\u201356]]{{Sfn|White|1989|p=381-384}}\n|29\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|29\n|2\n|-\n|[[1